{
  "query": "What is the comparative effectiveness of deploying acoustic devices on fishing gear, vessels, or moorings for reducing human-wildlife conflict at wild fisheries?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, acoustic devices deployed on fishing gear show the strongest evidence for effectiveness in reducing human-wildlife conflict, with 19 studies demonstrating significant benefits. Specifically, 14 studies showed reductions in entanglements and unwanted catch, while 6 studies demonstrated reduced damage to fish catches and fishing nets caused by marine mammals. In contrast, acoustic devices on fishing vessels have limited evidence for conflict reduction, with only one study finding no reduction in predation of squid catches by Risso's dolphins, though they did show behavioral effects on marine mammals in 4 studies. Acoustic devices on moorings have moderate evidence for effectiveness, with one study showing reduced harbor seal predation on migrating juvenile salmon and 7 studies demonstrating behavioral changes in marine mammals. The fishing gear deployment appears most effective for directly addressing human-wildlife conflict through reduced bycatch and gear damage, while vessel-based devices primarily affect animal behavior without clearly reducing conflict, and mooring-based devices show intermediate effectiveness with some conflict reduction benefits.",
