  "relevant_summary": "Legally protecting marine mammal habitats has shown mixed but generally positive population-level outcomes. Four studies evaluated habitat protection effects, showing: (1) A Mediterranean monk seal population increased during eight years after their island habitat was legally protected in the North Atlantic Ocean (Portugal); (2) A harbour seal population increased over 7-30 years after hunting was prohibited in the Kattegat and Skagerrak seas (Denmark and Sweden); (3) A bottlenose dolphin population remained similar in size before and after part of its range was protected in the North Sea (UK); (4) The survival rate of Hector's dolphins increased after a coastal area was legally protected in the South Pacific Ocean (New Zealand); (5) Human-caused strandings of Indo-Pacific bottlenose dolphins decreased after legal protection in the Port River estuary (Australia). Additionally, hunting prohibitions showed positive outcomes with four of five studies finding increased abundance of harbour seals and humpback whales over 7-30 years, and a review found significant increase rates for 10 of 12 baleen whale populations during 7-21 years after hunting prohibition legislation was introduced. No studies were found evaluating the effects of legally protecting marine and freshwater mammal species specifically or establishing networks of protected areas.",
