  "query": "What are the documented benefits and negative outcomes associated with captive rearing and rehabilitation of marine mammals?",
  "relevant_summary": "Documented benefits of captive rearing and rehabilitation of marine mammals include successful reproduction of released individuals, with one study finding that most captive-reared Antillean manatees reproduced after release. Survival rates vary by species, with approximately three-quarters of captive-reared Antillean manatees and two-thirds of Florida manatees surviving at least one year post-release. Captive-reared Pacific harbour seal pups showed survival similar to wild pups, and controlled breeding programs have produced viable offspring in some species.\n\nNegative outcomes include high mortality rates during and after rehabilitation, with some studies showing death before or after release, or individuals requiring return to captivity. One review found that most captive-born Amazon river dolphins, narrow-ridged finless porpoises, and Irrawaddy dolphins did not survive in captivity, and one controlled study found at least a quarter of California sea lions treated for toxic algae poisoning and released died or required euthanasia. Some captive-reared individuals displayed problematic post-release behaviors, such as travelling greater distances from release sites and showing reduced diving behaviors compared to wild counterparts, potentially affecting their ability to survive in natural environments. A Yangtze finless porpoise population maintained in semi-captive conditions had notably low genetic diversity.",
